      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the heavens and earth will rejoice,\n\tfor out of the north
        will come destroying armies\n\tagainst Babylon,\u201D says the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CJust as Babylon killed the people of Israel\n\tand others throughout
        the world,\n\tso must her people be killed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Get out, all you who have escaped the sword!\n\tDo not stand and
        watch\u2014flee while you can!\n\tRemember the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t,
        though you are in a far-off land,\n\tand think about your home in Jerusalem.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe are ashamed,\u201D the people say.\n\t\u201CWe are insulted
        and disgraced\n\tbecause the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s Temple\n\thas
        been defiled by foreigners.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes,\u201D says the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, \u201Cbut
        the time is coming\n\twhen I will destroy Babylon\u2019s idols.\n\tThe groans
        of her wounded people\n\twill be heard throughout the land.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Though Babylon reaches as high as the heavens\n\tand makes her fortifications
        incredibly strong,\n\tI will still send enemies to plunder her.\n\tI, the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, have spoken!  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Babylon\u2019s Complete Destruction"
      content: "\u201CListen! Hear the cry of Babylon,\n\tthe sound of great destruction
        from the land of the Babylonians.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is destroying Babylon.\n\tHe
        will silence her loud voice.\n\tWaves of enemies pound against her;\n\tthe
        noise of battle rings through the city.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Destroying armies come against Babylon.\n\tHer mighty men are captured,\n\tand
        their weapons break in their hands.\n\tFor the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is a God who gives just punishment;\n\the always repays in full.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will make her officials and wise men drunk,\n\talong with her captains,
        officers, and warriors.\n\tThey will fall asleep\n\tand never wake up again!\u201D\n\tsays
        the King, whose name is\n\tthe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s
        Armies.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s Armies
        says:\n\t\u201CThe thick walls of Babylon will be leveled to the ground,\n\tand
        her massive gates will be burned.\n\tThe builders from many lands have worked
        in vain,\n\tfor their work will be destroyed by fire!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Jeremiah\u2019s Message Sent to Babylon"
      content: "The prophet Jeremiah gave this message to Seraiah son of Neriah and
        grandson of Mahseiah, a staff officer, when Seraiah went to Babylon with
        King Zedekiah of Judah. This was during the fourth year of Zedekiah\u2019s
        reign.[COMMENT[0]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '51:59 '
        contents:
        - ft: "The fourth year of Zedekiah\u2019s reign was 593 "
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Jeremiah had recorded on a scroll all the terrible disasters that
        would soon come upon Babylon\u2014all the words written here. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said to Seraiah, \u201CWhen you get to Babylon, read aloud everything
        on this scroll. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then say, \u2018<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t, you have said that
        you will destroy Babylon so that neither people nor animals will remain here.
        She will lie empty and abandoned forever.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When you have finished reading the scroll, tie it to a stone and
        throw it into the Euphrates River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then say, \u2018In this same way Babylon and her people will sink,
        never again to rise, because of the disasters I will bring upon her.\u2019\u201D\n\tThis
        is the end of Jeremiah\u2019s messages."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Fall of Jerusalem
      content: 'Zedekiah was twenty-one years old when he became king, and he reigned
        in Jerusalem eleven years. His mother was Hamutal, the daughter of Jeremiah
        from Libnah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Zedekiah did what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        sight, just as Jehoiakim had done. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These things happened because of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        anger against the people of Jerusalem and Judah, until he finally banished
        them from his presence and sent them into exile.\n\tZedekiah rebelled against
        the king of Babylon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So on January 15,[COMMENT[0]] during the ninth year of Zedekiah\u2019s
        reign, King Nebuchadnezzar[COMMENT[1]] of Babylon led his entire army against
        Jerusalem. They surrounded the city and built siege ramps against its walls. "
      comments:
      - number: '52:4a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'on the tenth day of the tenth month, '
        - ft: 'of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar. A number of events in Jeremiah
            can be cross-checked with dates in surviving Babylonian records and related
            accurately to our modern calendar. This day was January 15, 588 '
          body: 
      - number: '52:4b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'Nebuchadrezzar, '
        - ft: a variant spelling of Nebuchadnezzar; also in 52:12, 28, 29, 30.
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Jerusalem was kept under siege until the eleventh year of King Zedekiah\u2019s
        reign.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "By July 18 in the eleventh year of Zedekiah\u2019s reign,[COMMENT[0]]
        the famine in the city had become very severe, and the last of the food was
        entirely gone. "
      comments:
      - number: '52:6 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'By the ninth day of the fourth month '
        - ft: "[in the eleventh year of Zedekiah\u2019s reign]. This day was July
            18, 586 "
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Then a section of the city wall was broken down, and all the soldiers
        fled. Since the city was surrounded by the Babylonians,[COMMENT[0]] they
        waited for nightfall. Then they slipped through the gate between the two
        walls behind the king\u2019s garden and headed toward the Jordan Valley.[COMMENT[1]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '52:7a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: 'the Chaldeans; '
        - ft: similarly in 52:8, 17.
          body: 
      - number: '52:7b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: the Arabah.
    - title: 
      content: 'But the Babylonian troops chased King Zedekiah and overtook him on
        the plains of Jericho, for his men had all deserted him and scattered. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They captured the king and took him to the king of Babylon at Riblah
        in the land of Hamath. There the king of Babylon pronounced judgment upon
        Zedekiah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The king of Babylon made Zedekiah watch as he slaughtered his sons.
        He also slaughtered all the officials of Judah at Riblah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he gouged out Zedekiah\u2019s eyes and bound him in bronze chains,
        and the king of Babylon led him away to Babylon. Zedekiah remained there
        in prison until the day of his death.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Temple Destroyed
      content: "On August 17 of that year,[COMMENT[0]] which was the nineteenth year
        of King Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s reign, Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard
        and an official of the Babylonian king, arrived in Jerusalem. "
      comments:
      - number: '52:12 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: 'On the tenth day of the fifth month, '
        - ft: 'of the ancient Hebrew lunar calendar. This day was August 17, 586 '
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "He burned down the Temple of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t,
        the royal palace, and all the houses of Jerusalem. He destroyed all the important
        buildings[COMMENT[0]] in the city. "
      comments:
      - number: '52:13 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: destroyed the houses of all the important people.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he supervised the entire Babylonian[COMMENT[0]] army as they
        tore down the walls of Jerusalem on every side. '
      comments:
      - number: '52:14 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Or '
          body: Chaldean.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, took as exiles some of
        the poorest of the people, the rest of the people who remained in the city,
        the defectors who had declared their allegiance to the king of Babylon, and
        the rest of the craftsmen. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Nebuzaradan allowed some of the poorest people to stay behind
        to care for the vineyards and fields.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Babylonians broke up the bronze pillars in front of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        Temple, the bronze water carts, and the great bronze basin called the Sea,
        and they carried all the bronze away to Babylon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They also took all the ash buckets, shovels, lamp snuffers, basins,
        dishes, and all the other bronze articles used for making sacrifices at the
        Temple. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The captain of the guard also took the small bowls, incense burners,
        basins, pots, lampstands, ladles, bowls used for liquid offerings, and all
        the other articles made of pure gold or silver.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The weight of the bronze from the two pillars, the Sea with the twelve
        bronze oxen beneath it, and the water carts was too great to be measured.
        These things had been made for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\n\t\u2019s
        Temple in the days of King Solomon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each of the pillars was 27 feet tall and 18 feet in circumference.[COMMENT[0]]
        They were hollow, with walls 3 inches thick.[COMMENT[1]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '52:21a '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '18 cubits '
        - ft: '[8.3 meters] '
          body: 'tall and 12 cubits '
        - ft: '[5.5 meters] '
          body: in circumference.
      - number: '52:21b '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '4 fingers thick '
        - ft: '[8 centimeters].'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'The bronze capital on top of each pillar was 7-1/2 feet[COMMENT[0]]
        high and was decorated with a network of bronze pomegranates all the way
        around. '
      comments:
      - number: '52:22 '
        contents:
        - ft: 'Hebrew '
          body: '5 cubits '
        - ft: '[2.3 meters].'
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: 'There were 96 pomegranates on the sides, and a total of 100 pomegranates
        on the network around the top.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, took with him as prisoners
        Seraiah the high priest, Zephaniah the priest of the second rank, and the
        three chief gatekeepers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And from among the people still hiding in the city, he took an officer
        who had been in charge of the Judean army; seven of the king\u2019s personal
        advisers; the army commander\u2019s chief secretary, who was in charge of
        recruitment; and sixty other citizens. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nebuzaradan, the captain of the guard, took them all to the king
        of Babylon at Riblah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And there at Riblah, in the land of Hamath, the king of Babylon had
        them all put to death. So the people of Judah were sent into exile from their
        land.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The number of captives taken to Babylon in the seventh year of Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s
        reign[COMMENT[0]] was 3,023. "
      comments:
      - number: '52:28 '
        contents:
        - ft: "This exile in the seventh year of Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s reign occurred
            in 597 "
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "Then in Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s eighteenth year[COMMENT[0]] he took
        832 more. "
      comments:
      - number: '52:29 '
        contents:
        - ft: "This exile in the eighteenth year of Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s reign occurred
            in 586 "
          body: 
    - title: 
      content: "In Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s twenty-third year[COMMENT[0]] he sent Nebuzaradan,
        the captain of the guard, who took 745 more\u2014a total of 4,600 captives
        in all.  "
      comments:
